WEBVTT

00:00.680 --> 00:02.380
Take a little bit of a break from React

00:02.380 --> 00:04.780
and we're gonna talk about tools,

00:04.780 --> 00:06.280
which seem to bother everyone but me.

00:06.280 --> 00:07.120
I love tools.

00:07.120 --> 00:09.000
That's why I've worked in DevTools for a very long time.

00:09.000 --> 00:13.680
I've shown you enough vanilla JavaScript React

00:13.680 --> 00:15.200
for you to know exactly what's happening

00:15.200 --> 00:16.200
underneath the hood.

00:17.680 --> 00:20.040
From here, we're gonna move into JSX,

00:20.040 --> 00:22.880
which was a huge barrier to adoption for a lot of people,

00:22.880 --> 00:24.360
especially early in the life of React,

00:24.360 --> 00:25.920
where they're like, hey, we don't really wanna write

00:25.920 --> 00:28.680
this compiled to JavaScript language.

00:28.680 --> 00:29.700
It feels weird.

00:32.160 --> 00:33.440
But we'll get there in just a second.

00:33.440 --> 00:34.920
For now, we're going to set up all the tools

00:34.920 --> 00:36.220
so that we can do that.

00:37.780 --> 00:41.120
So the first thing is we're gonna use NPM.

00:41.120 --> 00:43.880
I'm gonna use NPM for the life of this course.

00:43.880 --> 00:45.080
Feel free to use YARN.

00:45.080 --> 00:48.520
Previous versions of this course have used YARN before.

00:48.520 --> 00:51.200
PNPM, you can see I have a call out to that one as well.

00:51.200 --> 00:53.400
I think that's getting more and more popular.

00:54.900 --> 00:58.320
But it's kinda hard to go wrong with just straight up NPM.

00:59.080 --> 01:00.160
If you're not familiar with NPM,

01:00.160 --> 01:02.320
it does not stand for Node Package Manager,

01:03.800 --> 01:06.840
but it kinda stands for Node Package Manager.

01:06.840 --> 01:07.680
That's what they say.

01:07.680 --> 01:08.800
They say it doesn't stand for that.

01:08.800 --> 01:10.280
And then they just finish the sentence

01:10.280 --> 01:11.120
and don't say anything else.

01:11.120 --> 01:12.560
It's kind of annoying.

01:12.560 --> 01:14.920
Anyway, it is the package manager for Node.js.

01:16.160 --> 01:17.480
It allows you to install these things

01:17.480 --> 01:19.120
directly off of the NPM registry,

01:19.120 --> 01:20.600
which is now owned by GitHub,

01:20.600 --> 01:22.440
which is in turn owned by Microsoft.

01:25.360 --> 01:28.400
It allows you to do things like NPM install React,

01:28.400 --> 01:29.600
things like that.

01:29.600 --> 01:34.020
So in our project, let's go do the first thing here.

01:34.020 --> 01:35.800
You can go ahead and stop serve.

01:35.800 --> 01:38.160
We won't be using that anymore.

01:38.160 --> 01:42.920
That's Control C, if you're not familiar with Linux.

01:42.920 --> 01:46.920
All right, so I'm gonna do NPM init-y.

01:49.240 --> 01:50.480
The dash y just says,

01:50.480 --> 01:52.200
I don't wanna answer any of your dumb questions.

01:52.200 --> 01:53.520
Just generate a file for me.

01:53.520 --> 01:54.760
But if you wanna answer the questions,

01:54.760 --> 01:56.060
just leave off the dash y.

01:56.820 --> 01:58.620
And you'll see that you'll get out of here

01:58.620 --> 02:00.420
a package JSON here.

02:00.420 --> 02:03.420
And this allows you to start saving things to your project.

02:04.420 --> 02:05.940
The reason why this is useful to us

02:05.940 --> 02:09.020
is that we can say NPM install React.

02:09.020 --> 02:10.340
It'll go install React for us

02:10.340 --> 02:12.140
and it'll store the version of React

02:12.140 --> 02:13.660
that we're using in the project.

02:13.660 --> 02:15.620
So that when I share this with you later,

02:15.620 --> 02:16.740
you can go install it

02:16.740 --> 02:18.080
and you'll get the same version of React

02:18.080 --> 02:22.340
or a compatible version of React that I'm using.

02:22.340 --> 02:24.420
But I don't have to save React in my repo.

02:24.420 --> 02:26.660
So we don't have to have a trillion copies of React

02:26.660 --> 02:28.380
floating out on GitHub, right?

02:28.380 --> 02:30.260
We get one copy of React.

02:31.980 --> 02:35.020
And like if React has a critical vulnerability,

02:35.020 --> 02:36.660
like stuff like that happens,

02:36.660 --> 02:37.820
they're able to patch it

02:37.820 --> 02:39.380
so that next time you go to install,

02:39.380 --> 02:40.780
you'll get the patched version,

02:40.780 --> 02:42.580
not the insecure version.

02:44.820 --> 02:47.300
Okay, hopefully that worked for you.

02:47.300 --> 02:51.860
If not, you'll probably have to go to the Node.js page

02:51.860 --> 02:55.100
and install Node, however you choose to do that.

02:55.100 --> 03:00.100
But again, make sure you end up on Node 20.6 or above, please.

03:03.980 --> 03:05.060
Feel free to use pnpm.

03:05.060 --> 03:06.660
It does relatively the same thing.

03:06.660 --> 03:08.860
I'd be very, very confident

03:08.860 --> 03:11.260
that it would work just as well.

03:11.260 --> 03:12.580
Yarn, less so these days.

03:12.580 --> 03:14.300
I haven't used Yarn in a long time.

03:17.760 --> 03:20.460
You might've noticed when I've been writing code here

03:21.460 --> 03:24.340
that like if I do something like this and I,

03:24.340 --> 03:27.260
let's close this, come on.

03:29.140 --> 03:31.060
So if I do like this and I put a bunch of space

03:31.060 --> 03:32.740
and then whenever I hit save,

03:33.700 --> 03:34.540
oh, it doesn't like, did I?

03:34.540 --> 03:35.860
It's a slash on line 27.

03:35.860 --> 03:36.700
Oh, there you go, thank you.

03:36.700 --> 03:39.700
It just fixes all of my spacing for me automatically.

03:41.140 --> 03:44.060
I cannot be bothered to handle spacing anymore.

03:44.060 --> 03:46.220
Like that process in my brain

03:46.220 --> 03:48.500
that thinks about code formatting has just been shut down

03:48.500 --> 03:50.300
and at this point it's been shut down for so long

03:50.300 --> 03:51.860
that it's atrophied.

03:51.860 --> 03:54.820
So I literally cannot fathom how to write

03:54.820 --> 03:56.020
well-formatted code anymore

03:56.020 --> 03:58.260
because Prettier just does it for me automatically

03:58.260 --> 03:59.200
every single time.

04:00.900 --> 04:03.740
So all Prettier is is the code formatter.

04:03.740 --> 04:07.660
It takes in unformatted code and it spits out formatted code.

04:08.740 --> 04:11.220
It's my favorite tool in JavaScript ever.

04:11.220 --> 04:13.980
It's literally changed the way that I write code

04:13.980 --> 04:16.940
and blessed be to the Prettier gods.

04:17.780 --> 04:22.780
So let's go ahead and start this project for Prettier.

04:24.980 --> 04:27.980
All you have to do is create a file called .prettierrc

04:30.460 --> 04:34.780
and then I put the very controversial empty object

04:34.780 --> 04:39.780
as my config, which is just saying use all the defaults.

04:42.980 --> 04:45.740
My least favorite thing is bike shedding

04:45.780 --> 04:48.900
about code formatting.

04:48.900 --> 04:49.740
I hate it.

04:49.740 --> 04:51.420
I have been in so many meetings over the years

04:51.420 --> 04:53.620
with like we should be using tabs versus spaces

04:53.620 --> 04:57.780
or commas at the end or not commas

04:57.780 --> 05:01.560
or automated semicolon insertion or not,

05:01.560 --> 05:03.060
all those different things.

05:03.060 --> 05:08.060
And my message to you is I can't fathom any caring for it.

05:09.900 --> 05:12.840
I just, it's my least favorite thing to talk about.

05:12.840 --> 05:14.240
So that's why I put this empty object here

05:14.240 --> 05:16.800
is like whatever someone else chooses for me, I don't care.

05:16.800 --> 05:19.720
As long as it gets formatted in a uniform way, I don't care.

05:19.720 --> 05:20.720
So that's what that is.

05:20.720 --> 05:22.040
I have a VS code extension here.

05:22.040 --> 05:24.440
So if you're following along in VS code,

05:24.440 --> 05:28.480
I'm gonna suggest you install the Prettier code formatter.

05:29.960 --> 05:31.240
There's several, so make sure you get the one

05:31.240 --> 05:32.580
that's officially from Prettier

05:32.580 --> 05:35.120
and then go into one of your JS files

05:35.120 --> 05:40.000
and just you can hit, it's either shift command P on a Mac

05:40.000 --> 05:45.000
or control shift P on Linux and Windows

05:45.640 --> 05:48.040
and then choose format document.

05:49.960 --> 05:51.560
If this is your first time doing it, it's gonna say like,

05:51.560 --> 05:55.760
hey, you need to choose a formatter and just choose Prettier

05:55.760 --> 05:59.720
and then that'll set that up so that that formats

05:59.720 --> 06:02.920
your documents and then if you hit command comma

06:02.920 --> 06:07.680
or control comma and then you wanna do format on save

06:08.200 --> 06:11.280
and just make sure that that one's checked.

06:14.200 --> 06:18.240
Then you're ready to roll and then you'll get exactly

06:18.240 --> 06:21.160
the same thing so you can just like mess up formatting,

06:21.160 --> 06:23.520
make it terrible, let's de-indent everything

06:23.520 --> 06:25.480
because that just, it makes everyone able

06:25.480 --> 06:28.320
to look at that code and you just save it

06:28.320 --> 06:29.600
and it just fixes itself.

06:29.600 --> 06:32.200
I know I want everyone to use VS code

06:34.400 --> 06:36.000
but I also used to work with the Primogen.

06:36.040 --> 06:40.880
So not everyone's gonna use VS code, it turns out, right?

06:40.880 --> 06:42.680
So you need to set up all of your projects

06:42.680 --> 06:46.280
to work with anyone's tools, not just your own tool.

06:46.280 --> 06:49.160
So let's go ahead and set up Prettier to work with everybody.

06:49.160 --> 06:54.160
npm install dash dash save dev

06:55.200 --> 06:58.880
or if you're lazy like me, npm i dash capital D

06:58.880 --> 07:02.120
is the exact same thing and we're gonna put Prettier.

07:06.800 --> 07:11.720
And you can see here, we have a dev dependency, right?

07:11.720 --> 07:14.880
So this is a, this only needs to be installed

07:14.880 --> 07:17.280
in development environments, not for production environments.

07:17.280 --> 07:19.960
That's what the dev dependency means.

07:19.960 --> 07:24.960
And then under scripts, we're going to do this.

07:27.600 --> 07:32.600
I'm gonna set format and you're gonna do Prettier dash dash

07:32.680 --> 07:37.680
write and we're just gonna say,

07:39.560 --> 07:41.720
do everything in the source directory

07:49.200 --> 07:54.200
and then you need to do JS, JSX, TS, TSX,

07:54.560 --> 07:57.040
whatever file formats you want it to look at.

07:58.440 --> 07:59.920
That's probably a pretty good list.

07:59.920 --> 08:02.880
If you have, we're not gonna have any TypeScript in this.

08:02.880 --> 08:04.880
You could leave the TypeScript stuff out,

08:05.920 --> 08:09.360
but JS, JSX, CSS, you could put HTML in here as well.

08:11.840 --> 08:12.880
Prettier doesn't work with everything,

08:12.880 --> 08:14.400
but they're actually expanding it

08:14.400 --> 08:16.000
to a lot of other languages now.

08:17.560 --> 08:19.720
Make sure you need a comma there at the end.

08:23.040 --> 08:28.040
And now we should be able to run npm run format.

08:28.440 --> 08:30.040
That's what the scripts are for.

08:30.040 --> 08:33.400
It's basically like, please remember these bash commands

08:33.400 --> 08:34.680
for me so later, so I don't have to remember

08:34.680 --> 08:36.160
how to write this.

08:37.360 --> 08:40.240
You can just say npm run format and it'll run that for you.

08:40.240 --> 08:42.920
Oh, and I needed a closing quote here.

08:42.920 --> 08:45.440
Make sure you have the quotes here.

08:45.440 --> 08:48.480
The backslash is just an escape character, right?

08:48.480 --> 08:49.640
Reason why you want the quotes here

08:49.640 --> 08:52.280
is that you don't want your shell to do the file expansion.

08:52.280 --> 08:55.000
You want the actual, you want that passed in literally

08:55.000 --> 08:57.800
as a string to Prettier.

08:57.840 --> 09:00.640
So that it can go do all the finding of the correct files.

09:03.120 --> 09:04.600
Now mine's already running, right?

09:04.600 --> 09:06.320
Because every time I save the file, it's running,

09:06.320 --> 09:09.040
but you can see, so it says unchanged here.

09:09.040 --> 09:11.200
But if I had something to change there, it would say.

